{"title_page": "Project 21900 icebreaker", "text_new": "{{short description|Russian icebreakers}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Sankt-peterburg 2015-03-25.jpg\n|Ship image size=300px\n|Ship caption=''Sankt-Peterburg'', the second Project 21900 icebreaker, underway in [[Kara Sea]] in 2015\n}}\n|+\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Builders=* [[Baltic Shipyard]] ([[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]])\n* [[Vyborg Shipyard]] ([[Vyborg]], Russia)\n* [[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]] ([[Helsinki]], [[Finland]])\n* [[Pella Sietas]] ([[Hamburg]], [[Germany]]; planned)\n|Operators=[[Rosmorport]]\n|Class before=\n|Class after=\n|Subclasses=\n|Built range=* 2008\u20132009 (21900)\n* 2015\u20132016 (21900M)\n* 2023 (21900M2; planned)\n|In service range=\n|Total ships building=\n|Total ships planned=7\n|Total ships completed=5\n|Total ships cancelled=\n|Total ships active=\n|Total ships laid up=\n|Total ships lost=\n|Total ships retired=\n|Total ships scrapped=\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=[[Icebreaker]]\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement={{convert|14300|t|LT|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|114|-|119.8|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} ([[length overall|overall]])\n|Ship beam={{convert|27.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draft={{convert|8.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} (design)\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship ice class=[[Russian Maritime Register of Shipping|RMRS]] Icebreaker6\n|Ship power=Four [[diesel engine|diesel generating sets]]\n|Ship propulsion=[[Diesel-electric]]; two [[Steerprop]] [[azimuth thruster]]s (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}8.2\u20139{{nbsp}}MW)\n|Ship speed=* {{convert|16|-|17|kn}}\n* {{convert|3|-|3.5|kn}} in {{convert|1.0|m|ft|abbr=on}} ice\n|Ship range=<!-- {{convert|11000|nmi}} find source-->\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship capacity=<!-- {{convert|800|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} cargo deck{{br}}{{TEU|33}} find source -->\n|Ship crew=25<!-- 35+1{{br}}Accommodation for 58 find source-->\n|Ship aircraft facilities=Helideck for [[Ka-32]]/[[Ka-226]] (21900) or [[Mi-8]]<!--/Mi-17 find source --> (21900M)\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''Project 21900 icebreakers''' and their derivative designs are a series of [[Russia]]n [[diesel-electric]] [[icebreaker]]s built in the 2000s. They are also sometimes referred to using the type size series designation '''LK-16'''.<ref group=note>The type size series designation \"LK-16\" ({{lang-ru|\u041b\u041a-16}}) comes from the [[Russian language]] word for \"icebreaker\" ({{lang-ru|text=\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b|translit=ledokol}}) and the propulsion power (16 megawatts).</ref>\n\nThe two Project 21900 icebreakers built by [[Baltic Shipyard]], [[Moskva (2007 icebreaker)|''Moskva'']] and [[Sankt-Peterburg (icebreaker)|''Sankt-Peterburg'']], were the first non-nuclear icebreakers built by a Russian shipyard in over three decades and the first new icebreakers ordered following the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]]. Few years later, three additional icebreakers of a slightly improved design referred to as '''Project 21900M''' were ordered from [[Vyborg Shipyard]]: two vessels ([[Vladivostok (2014 icebreaker)|''Vladivostok'']] and [[Novorossiysk (icebreaker)|''Novorossiysk'']]) were built in Russia and the third ([[Murmansk (2015 icebreaker)|''Murmansk'']]) was subcontracted to the [[Finland|Finnish]] shipbuilder [[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]]. In 2019, one icebreaker of revised '''Project 21900M2''' design was ordered from [[Pella Sietas]].\n\n== Development and construction ==\n\n=== Project 21900 ===\n\nIn the early 2000s, Russia's state-owned icebreaker fleet consisted mainly of Soviet-era vessels dating back to the 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=\"oskjournal\">{{cite|url=https://www.aoosk.ru/upload/iblock/ba6/8_4_2011_arktika_.pdf|title=\u041b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u044f \u043b\u0435\u0434|page=24|journal=\u041e\u0421\u041a|volume=4|issue=8|year=2011|lang=ru|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> Whereas the [[Soviet Union]] had been steadily building up the world's largest icebreaker fleet, Russia had managed to commission only [[Yamal (icebreaker)|one nuclear-powered icebreaker]] during the decade following [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|its dissolution]]. In addition, the construction of [[50 Let Pobedy|another nuclear-powered icebreaker]] had been suspended in the mid-1990s due to lack of funds<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maritimemarket.ru/article.phtml?id=667&lang=en|title=Nuclear giant goes out to the Northern Sea route|first=Igor|last=Savelyev|publisher=Maritime Market|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> and a number of older diesel-powered icebreakers were written off in the 1990s.<ref>{{Citation|year=1998|title=Les D\u00e9fis Pour la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Europ\u00e9enne \u00c0 L'aube de L'an 2000: Strat\u00e9gies Pour Un D\u00e9veloppement Durable Des Etats Du Nord de L'Europe|publisher=Council of Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pD0ys7ejE1IC|page=94|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite efforts to extend the service life of the deteriorating Soviet-era icebreaker fleet and a number of private Russian companies acquiring their own icebreaking vessels to serve their needs, a fleet renewal plan was direly needed to avoid a situation where older icebreakers would be decommissioned before their replacements were ready.<ref name=\"oskjournal\" /> As a result, the federal program ''Modernization of the transport system of Russia (2002\u20132010)'' included recapitalizing the icebreaker fleet with a number of new vessels. Among these were two medium-sized diesel-electric icebreakers for service in the [[Gulf of Finland]] and [[Saint Petersburg]] area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pravo.gov.ru/proxy/ips/?docbody=&prevDoc=102089103&backlink=1&&nd=102073737|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0446\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0430 \"\u041c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043c\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 (2002-2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u044b)\"|lang=ru|publisher=Russian Government|date=5 December 2011|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2004, the [[Saint Petersburg]]-based [[Baltic Shipyard]] won an international tender for the construction of two 16-megawatt diesel-electric icebreakers for [[Rosmorport]], a state-owned company established in 2003 to manage Russia's port infrastructure and operate its fleet of diesel-powered icebreakers. The other bidders for the $150 million contract included the Finnish shipbuilders [[Kvaerner Masa-Yards]] and [[Aker Finnyards]] that had previously built a large number of icebreakers for the Soviet Union.<ref name=\"dpru_2004\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dp.ru/a/2004/10/21/Dlja_Primorska_postrojat_le|title=\u0414\u043b\u044f \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044f\u0442 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044b|lang=ru|publisher=dp.ru|date=21 October 2004|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> Although Baltic Shipyard had built five [[Arktika-class icebreaker|''Arktika''-class nuclear-powered icebreakers]] in 1975\u20131992 and had the sixth under construction at the time, these would be the first non-nuclear icebreakers built on a Russian shipyard in over three decades and the first new icebreakers ordered following the dissolution of the Soviet Union.<ref name=\"portnews_20081211\">{{cite web|url=http://en.portnews.ru/news/14106/|title=RosMorPort takes delivery of diesel-electric icebreaker Moskva built by Baltiysky Zavod|publisher=PortNews|date=11 December 2008|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> While the state budget did not initially allocate funding for the new icebreakers, the construction was nonetheless set to begin already in 2004 and the lead ship was to be delivered by November 2006.<ref name=\"dpru_2004\" /> \n\nThe lead ship of Project 21900 icebreakers, [[Moskva (2007 icebreaker)|''Moskva'']], was delivered on 11 December 2008 and the sister ship, [[Sankt-Peterburg (icebreaker)|''Sankt-Peterburg'']], on 12 July 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portnews.ru/comments/1196/|title=The Moskva to serve St. Petersburg|publisher=PortNews|date=12 December 2008|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ria.ru/20090713/177183932.html|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0443 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430|lang=ru|publisher=RIA Novosti|date=13 July 2009|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Project 21900M ===\n\nFollowing the challenging winter navigating season of 2010\u20132011, during which ice conditions in the Baltic Sea became so severe that Russia was forced to call in the [[nuclear-powered icebreaker]] [[Vaygach (1989 icebreaker)|''Vaygach'']] from [[Murmansk]] to escort ships in the eastern Gulf of Finland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltice.org/app/static/pdf/BIM%20Report%2010-11.pdf|title=Baltic Sea Icebreaking Sport 2010-2011|publisher=Baltic Icebreaking Management|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> the Russian government decided to continue the fleet renewal within the framework of the federal program ''Development of the Transport System of Russia (2010\u20132020)'' with three additional 16-megawatt diesel-electric icebreakers.<ref name=\"oskjournal\" /><ref name=\"acceptanceact\">{{cite web|url=http://portnews.ru/news/207912/|title=\u041f\u043e\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d \u0430\u043a\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043c\u0430-\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0447\u0438 \u0434\u0438\u0437\u0435\u043b\u044c-\u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u00ab\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u00bb (\u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e)|lang=ru|publisher=PortNews|date=9 October 2015|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> While the initial agreement was signed between Rosmorport and the state-owned [[United Shipbuilding Corporation]] (USC) at the Baltic Shipyard, the construction of the first icebreaker awarded to the non-USC-affiliated [[Vyborg Shipyard]] on 2 December 2011.<ref name=\"vsy_contract\">{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2011&month=12&novelty=403|title=Vyborg Shipyard JSC will construct icebreaking vessel|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|date=December 2012|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://portnews.ru/news/72888/|title=\u0412\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0417 \u0438 \u041e\u0421\u041a \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043e \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0434\u0438\u0437\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0449\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\u044e 16 \u043c\u0412\u0442|lang=ru|publisher=PortNews|date=5 December 2011|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> On 23 February 2012, the remaining two vessels were also contracted to Vyborg Shipyard which was simultaneously acquired by USC to solve the shipyard's financial problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2012&month=2&novelty=399|title=The contract for construction of two diesel-powered open sea icebreakers has signed|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|date=February 2012|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aoosk.ru/press-center/news/osk-spasaet-vyborgskiy-zavod/|title=\u041e\u0421\u041a \u0441\u043f\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0412\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0434|lang=ru|publisher=United Shipbuilding Corporation|date=23 February 2012|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> Hull assembly, outfitting and commissioning of one icebreaker was subcontracted to the Finnish shipbuilding company [[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]] which, at the time, was a joint venture between USC and a subsidiary of the South Korean [[STX Offshore & Shipbuilding]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2012&month=12&novelty=379|title=Next icebreaker project 21900M will be built by Vyborg Shipyard in cooperation with Arctech Helsinki Shipyard|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|date=December 2012|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe new icebreakers, referred to as Project 21900M, represented a further development of the preceding design.<ref name=\"oskjournal\" /> The lead ship, [[Vladivostok (2014 icebreaker)|''Vladivostok'']], was delivered by Vyborg Shipyard on 23 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2015&month=9&novelty=319|title=Official ceremony of lifting the National Flag on the prototype Icebreaker project 21900 M was held in St.-Petersburg|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|date=September 2015|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> She was followed by the Arctech-built [[Murmansk (2015 icebreaker)|''Murmansk'']] on 25 December 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2015&month=12&novelty=310|title=Icebreaker Murmansk project 21900M delivered to the customer at Vyborg Shipyard|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|date=December 2015|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> and the final vessel of the series, [[Novorossiysk (icebreaker)|''Novorossiysk'']], on 26 December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2016&month=12&novelty=296|title=Icebreaker Novorossiysk project 21900M delivered to the customer|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|accessdate=4 August 2019|date=27 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Project 21900M2 ===\n\nIn April 2019, Rosmorport contracted [[Vympel Design Bureau]] to develop a new 18-megawatt icebreaker concept based on the previous Project 21900M design. The new icebreaker, named Project 21900M2, would feature [[selective catalytic reduction]] (SCR) units and [[scrubber]]s to reduce [[NOx|nitrogen oxide]] (NOx) and [[sulfur oxide]] (SOx) emissions, respectively, as well as meet the requirements of the [[International Code for Ships Operating in Polar Waters]] (Polar Code).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.portnews.ru/news/276049/|title=VDB to develop design of an 18MW icebreaker for Rosmorport|publisher=PortNews|date=24 April 2019|accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.temann.ru/news/technology/item/nizhegorodskoe_kb_vympel_sproektiruet_ledokol_dlya_rosmorporta/|title=\u041d\u0438\u0436\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u041a\u0411 \u00ab\u0412\u044b\u043c\u043f\u0435\u043b\u00bb \u0441\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b \u0434\u043b\u044f \u00ab\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u00bb|lang=ru|publisher=Tema NN|date=15 May 2019|accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn August 2019, Rosmorport opened a [[Russian ruble|RUB]] 7,549,241,400 (about 100 million euro) tender for the construction of a 18-megawatt icebreaker to ensure year-round operation of the Russian Far East. According to the tender, the new icebreaker would be delivered by 30 September 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portnews.ru/news/281769/|title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0449\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\u044e 18 \u041c\u0412\u0442 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0437\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0414\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0412\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0430|lang=ru|publisher=PortNews|date=13 August 2019|accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> On 5 September 2019, it was announced that the contract was awarded to the [[Otradnoye, Kirovsky District, Leningrad Oblast|Otradnoye-based]] [[Pella Shipyard]] which was the only bidder.<ref name=\"pella\">{{cite web|url=http://sudostroenie.info/novosti/27959.html|title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b \u0434\u043b\u044f \"\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442 \u0421\u0417 \"\u041f\u0435\u043b\u043b\u0430\"|lang=ru|publisher=Sudostroenie.info|date=5 September 2019|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> However, construction of the vessel has been subcontracted to [[Pella Sietas]] in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]], for which the 100 million euro order is the biggest single contract in the company history.<ref name=\"pella2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hafen-hamburg.de/en/news/pella-sietas-gmbh-secures-construction-of-icebreaker-of-ice-class-icebreaker7-and-largest-single-order-in-company-history---36585|title=Pella Sietas GmbH secures construction of icebreaker of ice class \"Icebreaker7\" and largest single order in company history|publisher=Port of Hamburg|date=9 December 2019|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April 2020, Rosmorport opened a second tender for a similar icebreaker to be constructed for the Baltic Sea with delivery by 10 December 2024.<ref name=\"second21900m2\">{{cite web|url=http://portnews.ru/news/293821/|title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0449\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\u044e 18 \u041c\u0412\u0442 \u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0439 7,3 \u043c\u043b\u0440\u0434 \u0440\u0443\u0431.|publisher=PortNews|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n\nProject 21900 icebreakers are {{convert|114|m|ft|0}} [[length overall|long overall]] and have a moulded beam of {{convert|27.5|m|ft|0}}. Fully laden, the {{convert|14300|t|LT|adj=on}} icebreakers draw {{convert|8.5|m|ft|0}} of water.<ref name=\"rs_moskva\">{{csr|register=RS|id=050211|shipname=Moskva|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> While Project 21900M icebreakers are slightly longer at {{convert|119.8|m|ft}}, they have the same beam, design draught and displacement.<ref name=\"rs_vladivostok\">{{csr|register=RS|id=120113|shipname=Vladivostok|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The general layout of both designs is somewhat similar with the largest external difference being the helideck: Project 21900 icebreakers have a slightly smaller landing area located behind the superstructure while in Project 21900M and 21900M2 icebreakers the helideck has been moved to the forecastle and increased in size.<ref name=\"korabel\">{{cite web|url=https://www.korabel.ru/news/comments/murmansk_dlya_peterburga_kakov_ledokol_proekta_21900m.html|title=\"\u041c\u0443\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\" \u0434\u043b\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430: \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 21900\u041c?|lang=ru|publisher=Korabel.ru|date=16 April 2018|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nBoth Project 21900 and 21900M icebreakers have a fully integrated [[diesel-electric]] propulsion system with four main [[diesel generator]]s supplying power for both main propulsion as well as the ship's service loads while underway. In the first two vessels, the main power plant consists of two {{convert|4500|kW|hp|adj=on}} [[straight-nine engine|9-cylinder]] [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 9L32 and two {{convert|6000|kW|hp|adj=on}} [[V12 engine|12-cylinder]] W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 12V32 medium-speed [[diesel engine]]s.<ref name=\"rs_moskva\" /> In the three following vessels, all four main engines are identical 12-cylinder W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 12V32E units rated at {{convert|6960|kW|hp}} each.<ref name=\"rs_vladivostok\" /> In addition, all icebreakers have two W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 4L20 auxiliary diesel generators for use when the vessel is at port.<ref name=\"korabel\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sudostroenie.info/novosti/12309.html|title=\u041f\u043e\u0447\u0442\u0438 4 \u043c\u043b\u043d \u0440\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0437\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043a \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0443 \u00ab\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430\u00bb \u043e\u0442\u0434\u0430\u0441\u0442 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442|lang=ru|publisher=Sudostroenie.info|date=7 November 2014|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor main propulsion, both Project 21900 and 21900M icebreakers are fitted with two electrically driven [[Steerprop]] [[Z-drive]] [[azimuth thruster]]s with four-bladed stainless steel propellers. In the first two vessels, the propellers were in [[pusher configuration]] whereas the later icebreakers had more efficient [[tractor configuration|forward-facing propellers]]. Each propeller is driven by two electric propulsion motors in tandem: in Project 21900, they are rated at {{convert|4100|kW|hp|abbr=on}} each while in Project 21900M the motors have been uprated to {{convert|4500|kW|hp|adj=on}}. The resulting combined propulsion power output is about {{convert|16000|kW|hp}} (21900) to {{convert|18000|kW|hp}} (21900M). In addition, the icebreakers have a single transverse [[bow thruster]] for maneuvering.<ref name=\"rs_moskva\" /><ref name=\"rs_vladivostok\" /><ref name=\"korabel\" />\n\nProject 21900 icebreakers are strengthened to [[Russian Maritime Register of Shipping]] [[ice class]] ''Icebreaker6'' which is intended for icebreaking operations in non-Arctic freezing seas where the ice is up to {{convert|1.5|m|ft|0}} thick.<ref name=\"rs_moskva\" /> While officially the Project 21900M icebreakers have the same ice class,<ref name=\"rs_vladivostok\" /> their hulls and propulsion systems are strengthened to meet the requirements of ''Icebreaker7'' which is a higher ice class intended for icebreaking operations in the Arctic.<ref name=\"rosmorport_20140429\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rosmorport.com/news/company/24360/|title=Icebreaker of 21900M Project Hull Float Out Ceremony|publisher=Rosmorport|date=29 April 2014|accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"rules\">{{cite web|url=https://lk.rs-class.org/regbook/getDocument2?type=rules&d=73513281-E73C-417F-BB15-0EF448302439&f=73513281-E73C-417F-BB15-0EF448302439|title=Rules for the Classification and Construction of Sea-Going Ships, Part I: Classification|publisher=Russian Maritime Register of Shipping|year=2019|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Ships in class == \n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Name\n! Project\n! Builder\n! IMO number\n! Built\n! Status\n! Image\n! Ref\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Moskva (2007 icebreaker)|''Moskva'']]\n| align=\"center\" | 21900\n| align=\"center\" | [[Baltic Shipyard]] ([[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]])\n| align=\"center\" | {{IMO number|9326574|disp=no}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2008\n| align=\"center\" | In service\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:\u0421\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 '\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430'.jpg|200px]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"rs_moskva\" />\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Sankt-Peterburg (icebreaker)|''Sankt-Peterburg'']]\n| align=\"center\" | 21900\n| align=\"center\" | Baltic Shipyard (Saint Petersburg, Russia)\n| align=\"center\" | {{IMO number|9326586|disp=no}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2009\n| align=\"center\" | In service\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Sankt-Peterburg icebreaker (2229979).jpg|200px]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref>{{csr|register=RS|id=060054|shipname=Sankt-Peterburg|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n|- \n| align=\"left\" | [[Vladivostok (2014 icebreaker)|''Vladivostok'']]\n| align=\"center\" | 21900M\n| align=\"center\" | [[Vyborg Shipyard]] ([[Vyborg]], Russia)\n| align=\"center\" | {{IMO number|9658654|disp=no}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2015\n| align=\"center\" | In service\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Vladivostok icebreaker.JPG|200px]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref>{{csr|register=RS|id=120113|shipname=Vladivostok|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n|- \n| align=\"left\" | [[Murmansk (2015 icebreaker)|''Murmansk'']]\n| align=\"center\" | 21900M\n| align=\"center\" | [[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]] ([[Helsinki]], [[Finland]])\n| align=\"center\" | {{IMO number|9658666|disp=no}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2015\n| align=\"center\" | In service\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Helsinki, Finland (18962968838).jpg|200px]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref>{{csr|register=RS|id=120132|shipname=Murmansk|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-  \n| align=\"left\" | [[Novorossiysk (icebreaker)|''Novorossiysk'']]\n| align=\"center\" | 21900M\n| align=\"center\" | Vyborg Shipyard (Vyborg, Russia)\n| align=\"center\" | {{IMO number|9692571|disp=no}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2016\n| align=\"center\" | In service\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:V \u0424\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u0432 \u0421\u041f\u0431. \u041b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a.jpg|200px]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref>{{csr|register=RS|id=120128|shipname=Novorossiysk|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"\n| align=\"left\" | \n| align=\"center\" | 21900M2\n| align=\"center\" | [[Pella Sietas]] ([[Hamburg]], [[Germany]])\n| align=\"center\" | 9901374\n| align=\"center\" | 2023 (planned)\n| align=\"center\" | Ordered\n| align=\"center\" | \n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"pella2\" />\n|-style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"\n| align=\"left\" | \n| align=\"center\" | 21900M2\n| align=\"center\" | \n| align=\"center\" | \n| align=\"center\" | 2024 (planned)\n| align=\"center\" | Planned\n| align=\"center\" | \n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"second21900m2\" />\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Project 21900 icebreakers| ]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Russian icebreakers}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Sankt-peterburg 2015-03-25.jpg\n|Ship image size=300px\n|Ship caption=''Sankt-Peterburg'', the second Project 21900 icebreaker, underway in [[Kara Sea]] in 2015\n}}\n|+\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Builders=* [[Baltic Shipyard]] ([[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]])\n* [[Vyborg Shipyard]] ([[Vyborg]], Russia)\n* [[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]] ([[Helsinki]], [[Finland]])\n* [[Pella Sietas]] ([[Hamburg]], [[Germany]]; planned)\n|Operators=[[Rosmorport]]\n|Class before=\n|Class after=\n|Subclasses=\n|Built range=* 2008\u20132009 (21900)\n* 2015\u20132016 (21900M)\n* 2023 (21900M2; planned)\n|In service range=\n|Total ships building=\n|Total ships planned=6\n|Total ships completed=5\n|Total ships cancelled=\n|Total ships active=5\n|Total ships laid up=\n|Total ships lost=\n|Total ships retired=\n|Total ships scrapped=\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=[[Icebreaker]]\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement={{convert|14300|t|LT|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|114|-|119.8|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} ([[length overall|overall]])\n|Ship beam={{convert|27.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draft={{convert|8.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} (design)\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship ice class=[[Russian Maritime Register of Shipping|RMRS]] Icebreaker6\n|Ship power=Four [[diesel engine|diesel generating sets]]\n|Ship propulsion=[[Diesel-electric]]; two [[Steerprop]] [[azimuth thruster]]s (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}8.2\u20139{{nbsp}}MW)\n|Ship speed=* {{convert|16|-|17|kn}}\n* {{convert|3|-|3.5|kn}} in {{convert|1.0|m|ft|abbr=on}} ice\n|Ship range=<!-- {{convert|11000|nmi}} find source-->\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship capacity=<!-- {{convert|800|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} cargo deck{{br}}{{TEU|33}} find source -->\n|Ship crew=25<!-- 35+1{{br}}Accommodation for 58 find source-->\n|Ship aircraft facilities=Helideck for [[Ka-32]]/[[Ka-226]] (21900) or [[Mi-8]]<!--/Mi-17 find source --> (21900M)\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''Project 21900 icebreakers''' and their derivative designs are a series of [[Russia]]n [[diesel-electric]] [[icebreaker]]s built in the 2000s. They are also sometimes referred to using the type size series designation '''LK-16'''.<ref group=note>The type size series designation \"LK-16\" ({{lang-ru|\u041b\u041a-16}}) comes from the [[Russian language]] word for \"icebreaker\" ({{lang-ru|text=\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b|translit=ledokol}}) and the propulsion power (16 megawatts).</ref>\n\nThe two Project 21900 icebreakers built by [[Baltic Shipyard]], [[Moskva (2007 icebreaker)|''Moskva'']] and [[Sankt-Peterburg (icebreaker)|''Sankt-Peterburg'']], were the first non-nuclear icebreakers built by a Russian shipyard in over three decades and the first new icebreakers ordered following the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]]. Few years later, three additional icebreakers of a slightly improved design referred to as '''Project 21900M''' were ordered from [[Vyborg Shipyard]]: two vessels ([[Vladivostok (2014 icebreaker)|''Vladivostok'']] and [[Novorossiysk (icebreaker)|''Novorossiysk'']]) were built in Russia and the third ([[Murmansk (2015 icebreaker)|''Murmansk'']]) was subcontracted to the [[Finland|Finnish]] shipbuilder [[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]]. In 2019, one icebreaker of revised '''Project 21900M2''' design was ordered from [[Pella Sietas]].\n\n== Development and construction ==\n\n=== Project 21900 ===\n\nIn the early 2000s, Russia's state-owned icebreaker fleet consisted mainly of Soviet-era vessels dating back to the 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=\"oskjournal\">{{cite|url=https://www.aoosk.ru/upload/iblock/ba6/8_4_2011_arktika_.pdf|title=\u041b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u044f \u043b\u0435\u0434|page=24|journal=\u041e\u0421\u041a|volume=4|issue=8|year=2011|lang=ru|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> Whereas the [[Soviet Union]] had been steadily building up the world's largest icebreaker fleet, Russia had managed to commission only [[Yamal (icebreaker)|one nuclear-powered icebreaker]] during the decade following [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|its dissolution]]. In addition, the construction of [[50 Let Pobedy|another nuclear-powered icebreaker]] had been suspended in the mid-1990s due to lack of funds<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maritimemarket.ru/article.phtml?id=667&lang=en|title=Nuclear giant goes out to the Northern Sea route|first=Igor|last=Savelyev|publisher=Maritime Market|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> and a number of older diesel-powered icebreakers were written off in the 1990s.<ref>{{Citation|year=1998|title=Les D\u00e9fis Pour la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Europ\u00e9enne \u00c0 L'aube de L'an 2000: Strat\u00e9gies Pour Un D\u00e9veloppement Durable Des Etats Du Nord de L'Europe|publisher=Council of Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pD0ys7ejE1IC|page=94|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite efforts to extend the service life of the deteriorating Soviet-era icebreaker fleet and a number of private Russian companies acquiring their own icebreaking vessels to serve their needs, a fleet renewal plan was direly needed to avoid a situation where older icebreakers would be decommissioned before their replacements were ready.<ref name=\"oskjournal\" /> As a result, the federal program ''Modernization of the transport system of Russia (2002\u20132010)'' included recapitalizing the icebreaker fleet with a number of new vessels. Among these were two medium-sized diesel-electric icebreakers for service in the [[Gulf of Finland]] and [[Saint Petersburg]] area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pravo.gov.ru/proxy/ips/?docbody=&prevDoc=102089103&backlink=1&&nd=102073737|title=\u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0446\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u0430 \"\u041c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043c\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 (2002-2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u044b)\"|lang=ru|publisher=Russian Government|date=5 December 2011|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2004, the [[Saint Petersburg]]-based [[Baltic Shipyard]] won an international tender for the construction of two 16-megawatt diesel-electric icebreakers for [[Rosmorport]], a state-owned company established in 2003 to manage Russia's port infrastructure and operate its fleet of diesel-powered icebreakers. The other bidders for the $150 million contract included the Finnish shipbuilders [[Kvaerner Masa-Yards]] and [[Aker Finnyards]] that had previously built a large number of icebreakers for the Soviet Union.<ref name=\"dpru_2004\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dp.ru/a/2004/10/21/Dlja_Primorska_postrojat_le|title=\u0414\u043b\u044f \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044f\u0442 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044b|lang=ru|publisher=dp.ru|date=21 October 2004|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> Although Baltic Shipyard had built five [[Arktika-class icebreaker|''Arktika''-class nuclear-powered icebreakers]] in 1975\u20131992 and had the sixth under construction at the time, these would be the first non-nuclear icebreakers built on a Russian shipyard in over three decades and the first new icebreakers ordered following the dissolution of the Soviet Union.<ref name=\"portnews_20081211\">{{cite web|url=http://en.portnews.ru/news/14106/|title=RosMorPort takes delivery of diesel-electric icebreaker Moskva built by Baltiysky Zavod|publisher=PortNews|date=11 December 2008|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> While the state budget did not initially allocate funding for the new icebreakers, the construction was nonetheless set to begin already in 2004 and the lead ship was to be delivered by November 2006.<ref name=\"dpru_2004\" /> \n\nThe lead ship of Project 21900 icebreakers, [[Moskva (2007 icebreaker)|''Moskva'']], was delivered on 11 December 2008 and the sister ship, [[Sankt-Peterburg (icebreaker)|''Sankt-Peterburg'']], on 12 July 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portnews.ru/comments/1196/|title=The Moskva to serve St. Petersburg|publisher=PortNews|date=12 December 2008|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ria.ru/20090713/177183932.html|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0443 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430|lang=ru|publisher=RIA Novosti|date=13 July 2009|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Project 21900M ===\n\nFollowing the challenging winter navigating season of 2010\u20132011, during which ice conditions in the Baltic Sea became so severe that Russia was forced to call in the [[nuclear-powered icebreaker]] [[Vaygach (1989 icebreaker)|''Vaygach'']] from [[Murmansk]] to escort ships in the eastern Gulf of Finland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltice.org/app/static/pdf/BIM%20Report%2010-11.pdf|title=Baltic Sea Icebreaking Sport 2010-2011|publisher=Baltic Icebreaking Management|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> the Russian government decided to continue the fleet renewal within the framework of the federal program ''Development of the Transport System of Russia (2010\u20132020)'' with three additional 16-megawatt diesel-electric icebreakers.<ref name=\"oskjournal\" /><ref name=\"acceptanceact\">{{cite web|url=http://portnews.ru/news/207912/|title=\u041f\u043e\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d \u0430\u043a\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043c\u0430-\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0447\u0438 \u0434\u0438\u0437\u0435\u043b\u044c-\u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u00ab\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u00bb (\u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e)|lang=ru|publisher=PortNews|date=9 October 2015|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> While the initial agreement was signed between Rosmorport and the state-owned [[United Shipbuilding Corporation]] (USC) at the Baltic Shipyard, the construction of the first icebreaker awarded to the non-USC-affiliated [[Vyborg Shipyard]] on 2 December 2011.<ref name=\"vsy_contract\">{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2011&month=12&novelty=403|title=Vyborg Shipyard JSC will construct icebreaking vessel|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|date=December 2012|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://portnews.ru/news/72888/|title=\u0412\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0417 \u0438 \u041e\u0421\u041a \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043e \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0434\u0438\u0437\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0449\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\u044e 16 \u043c\u0412\u0442|lang=ru|publisher=PortNews|date=5 December 2011|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> On 23 February 2012, the remaining two vessels were also contracted to Vyborg Shipyard which was simultaneously acquired by USC to solve the shipyard's financial problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2012&month=2&novelty=399|title=The contract for construction of two diesel-powered open sea icebreakers has signed|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|date=February 2012|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aoosk.ru/press-center/news/osk-spasaet-vyborgskiy-zavod/|title=\u041e\u0421\u041a \u0441\u043f\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0412\u044b\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0434|lang=ru|publisher=United Shipbuilding Corporation|date=23 February 2012|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> Hull assembly, outfitting and commissioning of one icebreaker was subcontracted to the Finnish shipbuilding company [[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]] which, at the time, was a joint venture between USC and a subsidiary of the South Korean [[STX Offshore & Shipbuilding]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2012&month=12&novelty=379|title=Next icebreaker project 21900M will be built by Vyborg Shipyard in cooperation with Arctech Helsinki Shipyard|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|date=December 2012|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe new icebreakers, referred to as Project 21900M, represented a further development of the preceding design.<ref name=\"oskjournal\" /> The lead ship, [[Vladivostok (2014 icebreaker)|''Vladivostok'']], was delivered by Vyborg Shipyard on 23 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2015&month=9&novelty=319|title=Official ceremony of lifting the National Flag on the prototype Icebreaker project 21900 M was held in St.-Petersburg|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|date=September 2015|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> She was followed by the Arctech-built [[Murmansk (2015 icebreaker)|''Murmansk'']] on 25 December 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2015&month=12&novelty=310|title=Icebreaker Murmansk project 21900M delivered to the customer at Vyborg Shipyard|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|date=December 2015|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> and the final vessel of the series, [[Novorossiysk (icebreaker)|''Novorossiysk'']], on 26 December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vyborgshipyard.ru/en/rubric/na-angliyskom?year=2016&month=12&novelty=296|title=Icebreaker Novorossiysk project 21900M delivered to the customer|publisher=Vyborg Shipyard|accessdate=4 August 2019|date=27 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Project 21900M2 ===\n\nIn April 2019, Rosmorport contracted [[Vympel Design Bureau]] to develop a new 18-megawatt icebreaker concept based on the previous Project 21900M design. The new icebreaker, named Project 21900M2, would feature [[selective catalytic reduction]] (SCR) units and [[scrubber]]s to reduce [[NOx|nitrogen oxide]] (NOx) and [[sulfur oxide]] (SOx) emissions, respectively, as well as meet the requirements of the [[International Code for Ships Operating in Polar Waters]] (Polar Code).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.portnews.ru/news/276049/|title=VDB to develop design of an 18MW icebreaker for Rosmorport|publisher=PortNews|date=24 April 2019|accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.temann.ru/news/technology/item/nizhegorodskoe_kb_vympel_sproektiruet_ledokol_dlya_rosmorporta/|title=\u041d\u0438\u0436\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u041a\u0411 \u00ab\u0412\u044b\u043c\u043f\u0435\u043b\u00bb \u0441\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b \u0434\u043b\u044f \u00ab\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u00bb|lang=ru|publisher=Tema NN|date=15 May 2019|accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn August 2019, Rosmorport opened a [[Russian ruble|RUB]] 7,549,241,400 (about 100 million euro) tender for the construction of a 18-megawatt icebreaker to ensure year-round operation of the Russian Far East. According to the tender, the new icebreaker would be delivered by 30 September 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portnews.ru/news/281769/|title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0449\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\u044e 18 \u041c\u0412\u0442 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0437\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0414\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0412\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0430|lang=ru|publisher=PortNews|date=13 August 2019|accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> On 5 September 2019, it was announced that the contract was awarded to the [[Otradnoye, Kirovsky District, Leningrad Oblast|Otradnoye-based]] [[Pella Shipyard]] which was the only bidder.<ref name=\"pella\">{{cite web|url=http://sudostroenie.info/novosti/27959.html|title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b \u0434\u043b\u044f \"\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442 \u0421\u0417 \"\u041f\u0435\u043b\u043b\u0430\"|lang=ru|publisher=Sudostroenie.info|date=5 September 2019|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> However, construction of the vessel has been subcontracted to [[Pella Sietas]] in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]], for which the 100 million euro order is the biggest single contract in the company history.<ref name=\"pella2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hafen-hamburg.de/en/news/pella-sietas-gmbh-secures-construction-of-icebreaker-of-ice-class-icebreaker7-and-largest-single-order-in-company-history---36585|title=Pella Sietas GmbH secures construction of icebreaker of ice class \"Icebreaker7\" and largest single order in company history|publisher=Port of Hamburg|date=9 December 2019|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April 2020, Rosmorport opened a second tender for a similar icebreaker to be constructed for the Baltic Sea with delivery by 10 December 2024.<ref name=\"second21900m2\">{{cite web|url=http://portnews.ru/news/293821/|title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0449\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\u044e 18 \u041c\u0412\u0442 \u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0439 7,3 \u043c\u043b\u0440\u0434 \u0440\u0443\u0431.|publisher=PortNews|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n\nProject 21900 icebreakers are {{convert|114|m|ft|0}} [[length overall|long overall]] and have a moulded beam of {{convert|27.5|m|ft|0}}. Fully laden, the {{convert|14300|t|LT|adj=on}} icebreakers draw {{convert|8.5|m|ft|0}} of water.<ref name=\"rs_moskva\">{{csr|register=RS|id=050211|shipname=Moskva|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> While Project 21900M icebreakers are slightly longer at {{convert|119.8|m|ft}}, they have the same beam, design draught and displacement.<ref name=\"rs_vladivostok\">{{csr|register=RS|id=120113|shipname=Vladivostok|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> The general layout of both designs is somewhat similar with the largest external difference being the helideck: Project 21900 icebreakers have a slightly smaller landing area located behind the superstructure while in Project 21900M and 21900M2 icebreakers the helideck has been moved to the forecastle and increased in size.<ref name=\"korabel\">{{cite web|url=https://www.korabel.ru/news/comments/murmansk_dlya_peterburga_kakov_ledokol_proekta_21900m.html|title=\"\u041c\u0443\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\" \u0434\u043b\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430: \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 21900\u041c?|lang=ru|publisher=Korabel.ru|date=16 April 2018|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nBoth Project 21900 and 21900M icebreakers have a fully integrated [[diesel-electric]] propulsion system with four main [[diesel generator]]s supplying power for both main propulsion as well as the ship's service loads while underway. In the first two vessels, the main power plant consists of two {{convert|4500|kW|hp|adj=on}} [[straight-nine engine|9-cylinder]] [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 9L32 and two {{convert|6000|kW|hp|adj=on}} [[V12 engine|12-cylinder]] W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 12V32 medium-speed [[diesel engine]]s.<ref name=\"rs_moskva\" /> In the three following vessels, all four main engines are identical 12-cylinder W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 12V32E units rated at {{convert|6960|kW|hp}} each.<ref name=\"rs_vladivostok\" /> In addition, all icebreakers have two W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 4L20 auxiliary diesel generators for use when the vessel is at port.<ref name=\"korabel\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sudostroenie.info/novosti/12309.html|title=\u041f\u043e\u0447\u0442\u0438 4 \u043c\u043b\u043d \u0440\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0437\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043a \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0443 \u00ab\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430\u00bb \u043e\u0442\u0434\u0430\u0441\u0442 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442|lang=ru|publisher=Sudostroenie.info|date=7 November 2014|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor main propulsion, both Project 21900 and 21900M icebreakers are fitted with two electrically driven [[Steerprop]] [[Z-drive]] [[azimuth thruster]]s with four-bladed stainless steel propellers. In the first two vessels, the propellers were in [[pusher configuration]] whereas the later icebreakers had more efficient [[tractor configuration|forward-facing propellers]]. Each propeller is driven by two electric propulsion motors in tandem: in Project 21900, they are rated at {{convert|4100|kW|hp|abbr=on}} each while in Project 21900M the motors have been uprated to {{convert|4500|kW|hp|adj=on}}. The resulting combined propulsion power output is about {{convert|16000|kW|hp}} (21900) to {{convert|18000|kW|hp}} (21900M). In addition, the icebreakers have a single transverse [[bow thruster]] for maneuvering.<ref name=\"rs_moskva\" /><ref name=\"rs_vladivostok\" /><ref name=\"korabel\" />\n\nProject 21900 icebreakers are strengthened to [[Russian Maritime Register of Shipping]] [[ice class]] ''Icebreaker6'' which is intended for icebreaking operations in non-Arctic freezing seas where the ice is up to {{convert|1.5|m|ft|0}} thick.<ref name=\"rs_moskva\" /> While officially the Project 21900M icebreakers have the same ice class,<ref name=\"rs_vladivostok\" /> their hulls and propulsion systems are strengthened to meet the requirements of ''Icebreaker7'' which is a higher ice class intended for icebreaking operations in the Arctic.<ref name=\"rosmorport_20140429\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rosmorport.com/news/company/24360/|title=Icebreaker of 21900M Project Hull Float Out Ceremony|publisher=Rosmorport|date=29 April 2014|accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"rules\">{{cite web|url=https://lk.rs-class.org/regbook/getDocument2?type=rules&d=73513281-E73C-417F-BB15-0EF448302439&f=73513281-E73C-417F-BB15-0EF448302439|title=Rules for the Classification and Construction of Sea-Going Ships, Part I: Classification|publisher=Russian Maritime Register of Shipping|year=2019|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Ships in class == \n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Name\n! Project\n! Builder\n! IMO number\n! Built\n! Status\n! Image\n! Ref\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Moskva (2007 icebreaker)|''Moskva'']]\n| align=\"center\" | 21900\n| align=\"center\" | [[Baltic Shipyard]] ([[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]])\n| align=\"center\" | {{IMO number|9326574|disp=no}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2008\n| align=\"center\" | In service\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:\u0421\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 '\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430'.jpg|200px]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"rs_moskva\" />\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Sankt-Peterburg (icebreaker)|''Sankt-Peterburg'']]\n| align=\"center\" | 21900\n| align=\"center\" | Baltic Shipyard (Saint Petersburg, Russia)\n| align=\"center\" | {{IMO number|9326586|disp=no}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2009\n| align=\"center\" | In service\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Sankt-Peterburg icebreaker (2229979).jpg|200px]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref>{{csr|register=RS|id=060054|shipname=Sankt-Peterburg|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n|- \n| align=\"left\" | [[Vladivostok (2014 icebreaker)|''Vladivostok'']]\n| align=\"center\" | 21900M\n| align=\"center\" | [[Vyborg Shipyard]] ([[Vyborg]], Russia)\n| align=\"center\" | {{IMO number|9658654|disp=no}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2015\n| align=\"center\" | In service\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Vladivostok icebreaker.JPG|200px]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref>{{csr|register=RS|id=120113|shipname=Vladivostok|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n|- \n| align=\"left\" | [[Murmansk (2015 icebreaker)|''Murmansk'']]\n| align=\"center\" | 21900M\n| align=\"center\" | [[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]] ([[Helsinki]], [[Finland]])\n| align=\"center\" | {{IMO number|9658666|disp=no}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2015\n| align=\"center\" | In service\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:Helsinki, Finland (18962968838).jpg|200px]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref>{{csr|register=RS|id=120132|shipname=Murmansk|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-  \n| align=\"left\" | [[Novorossiysk (icebreaker)|''Novorossiysk'']]\n| align=\"center\" | 21900M\n| align=\"center\" | Vyborg Shipyard (Vyborg, Russia)\n| align=\"center\" | {{IMO number|9692571|disp=no}}\n| align=\"center\" | 2016\n| align=\"center\" | In service\n| align=\"center\" | [[File:V \u0424\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u0432 \u0421\u041f\u0431. \u041b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a.jpg|200px]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref>{{csr|register=RS|id=120128|shipname=Novorossiysk|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"\n| align=\"left\" | \n| align=\"center\" | 21900M2\n| align=\"center\" | [[Pella Sietas]] ([[Hamburg]], [[Germany]])\n| align=\"center\" | 9901374\n| align=\"center\" | 2023 (planned)\n| align=\"center\" | Ordered\n| align=\"center\" | \n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"pella2\" />\n|-style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"\n| align=\"left\" | \n| align=\"center\" | 21900M2\n| align=\"center\" | \n| align=\"center\" | \n| align=\"center\" | 2024 (planned)\n| align=\"center\" | Planned\n| align=\"center\" | \n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"second21900m2\" />\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Project 21900 icebreakers| ]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Tupsumato", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Project_21900_icebreaker"}
{"title_page": "Dedman School of Law", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{peacock|date=November 2017}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox law school\n|name            = Dedman School of Law\n|native_name     =\n|latin_name      =\n|motto           = ''Veritas Liberabit Vos''\n|mottoeng        = ''The Truth Shall Set You Free''\n|image           = SMU Dedman Law.png\n|image_size      = 300px\n|established     = 1925\n|type            = [[Private university|Private]]\n|endowment       = $1.633 billion (parent institution for FY 2019)\n|faculty         = 50 full-time; 10 emeritus; 94 adjunct\n|dean            = Jennifer M. Collins\n|coordinates     = {{coord|32.8464|-96.7861|type:edu_region:US-TX|display=it}}\n|students        = 900\n|ranking         = 56nd (2021)<ref>{{cite web |title=Southern Methodist University (Dedman) |url=https://premium.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/southern-methodist-university-03150}}</ref>\n|city            = [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]\n|state           = [[Texas]]\n|country         = U.S.\n|campus          = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|affiliations    =\n|parent          = [[Southern Methodist University]]\n|website         = {{url|www.law.smu.edu}}\n}}\n\n'''SMU Dedman School of Law''', commonly referred to as '''SMU Law School''' or '''Dedman School of Law'''  is a prominent professional [[graduate school|graduate]] [[law school]] located in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]]. It was founded in February 1925. SMU Law School is located on the  campus of its parent institution, [[Southern Methodist University]]\n\nSMU\u2019s Law School was renamed SMU Dedman School of Law in February 2001 in honor of its late benefactors, [[Robert H. Dedman Sr.]] and his wife, Nancy Dedman. SMU Law School was the only law school in Dallas until UNT opened its law school four years ago. The current dean of the law school is Jennifer Collins.\n\nSome of the Law School\u2019s alumni include White House Counsel, Chairs of the House Judiciary Committee, Foreign Minister of India, Chief Justices of Indonesia and Thailand, and the Chief Legal Counsel of AT&T and Mark Cuban Companies.\n\nSMU Dedman School of Law is one of ten law schools in Texas. The school has graduated five Fortune 500 Chief Executives (the most of any school according to Business Insider), justices of the Texas Supreme Court, federal and state judges, and several U.S. and state government officials, senators, and representatives.<br />\n\n<br />\n\n==Academic Profile==\nSMU Dedman School of Law offers [[Juris Doctor]], [[Master of Laws]], and [[Doctor of Juridical Science]] degrees.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.law.smu.edu/Default.aspx?DN=724ecf69-7fc0-4f58-956f-4640dd453d70 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-07-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815075056/http://www.law.smu.edu/Default.aspx?DN=724ecf69-7fc0-4f58-956f-4640dd453d70 |archive-date=2009-08-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The school offers two joint degree programs, a J.D./M.A. in Economics and a J.D./M.B.A. The J.D./M.A. in Economics is offered in connection with the SMU Department of Economics in [[Dedman College]] and the J.D./M.B.A. is offered in connection with the [[Cox School of Business]].[[File:SMU Dallas.jpg|thumb|266x266px|Aerial view of the SMU Campus with downtown Dallas]]The class that enrolled in the fall of 2019 has a median LSAT score of 161 and a median undergraduate GPA of 3.7. LSAT/UGPA medians were calculated by the Law School Admission Council based on matriculant lists provided by the law school to the American Bar Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu/Law/Admissions/FAQs|title=FAQs {{!}} SMU Dedman School of Law {{!}} Dallas Texas|website=www.smu.edu|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\nEach JD student must complete 87 credit hours. Thirty-one of these hours comprise the mandatory first-year curriculum. After the first year, students must complete a course in professional responsibility, two upper-level writing courses (including an edited writing seminar in which an extensive scholarly, expository writing project is reviewed and critiqued by the professor), Constitutional Law II, and a practical skills course.  All students are required to perform 30 hours of public service before graduating. <br />\n\n==Programs and Resources==\nDedman Law is home to five independent [[law journals]]: ''The SMU Law Review'', ''[[The International Lawyer]]'', ''Journal of Air Law and Commerce'', ''[[Law and Business Review of the Americas]]'', and the ''SMU Science & Technology Law Review''.\n\nServing the community since 1947, Dedman Law offers several [[law clinic]]s for upper-division students where, under the supervision of clinic directors, our students serve as advocates on behalf of the community in many areas of the law.  The law clinics include: the W.W. Caruth, Jr. Child Advocacy Clinic, Civil Clinic, Criminal Justice Clinic, Family Immigration Detention Clinic, Federal Taxpayers Clinic, First Amendment Clinic, Consumer Advocacy Project, Small Business Clinic & Trademark Clinic, Judge Elmo B. Hunter Legal Center for Victims of Crimes Against Women, Innocence Clinic, Patent Law Clinic, and Vansickle Family Law Clinic.\n\nDedman Law offers a summer program at the [[University of Oxford]] in [[Oxford, England]], numerous international programs, and Underwood Law Library.\n[[File:Underwood Library.jpg|thumb|SMU Underwood Library|291x291px]]\n\n==Underwood Law Library==\nSMU\u2019s Underwood Law Library is the largest private academic law library west of the Mississippi River .<ref name=\"smu.edu\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu/Law/Library/About|title=Archived copy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814095627/http://library.law.smu.edu/About-Us/Library-Facts|archive-date=2016-08-14|access-date=2016-07-13}}</ref> Its collections include approximately 662,465 law-related volumes and equivalents, ranking the library among the top 20% of all law libraries in the United States.<ref name=\"smu.edu\"/>\n\n==Rankings==\nIn 2020, SMU Dedman School of Law was ranked No. 56 in the nation by [[U.S. News & World Report]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://premium.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/southern-methodist-university-03150|title=Archived copy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Wv34IyBQ?url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-rankings/page+2|archive-date=2015-03-10|access-date=2014-03-11}}</ref>\n\nThe ''National Law Journal'' has ranked SMU Dedman School of Law 28th in \u201cgo-to\u201d law schools.\n\n''Business Insider'' ranked SMU Dedman School of Law 21st in Law schools that have the best alumni for networking and finding legal jobs and 32nd overall. SmartClass ranked Dedman between 24th and 37th in the nation from 2008 until today rising every year since the ranking's inception.\n\nThe school was ranked 8th in the nation for Tax Law and 3rd in the nation for real estate law by [[Law Street Media]].\n\nSSRN ranked Dedman in the top 30 law schools utilizing a new methodology that assimilates bar passage rates, employment statistics, Professor access, and other actual performance metrics that accentuate output as opposed to input, such as LSAT scores or undergraduate GPA.\n\nAmong all publications, SMU Law places between 19th and 46th. Excluding their highest and lowest ranking they consistently rank within the top 20\u201330 institutions in America. The school boasts a strong alumni class, top regional placement, and consistently robust employment outcomes (employed 92% of 2018 class within 9 months of graduation and 24% in the NLJ 250).\n\n==Employment==\n[[File:SMU Graduation.jpg|thumb|244x244px|Dedman School of Law Graduates]]\nAccording to SMU's official 2018 ABA-required disclosures, 80% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time, long-term, JD-required employment nine months after graduation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu/Law/Career-Services/Employment-Statistics/ABA-Employment-Summary-for-Class-of-2018|title=Archived copy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704072339/http://www.law.smu.edu/Career-Services/Employment-Statistics.aspx|archive-date=2014-07-04|access-date=2014-07-10}}</ref> SMU's [[Law School Transparency]] under-employment score is 10.8%, indicating the percentage of the Class of 2018 unemployed, pursuing an additional degree, or working in a non-professional, short-term, or part-time job nine months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lstreports.com/schools/smu/|title=Southern Methodist University|last=|first=|date=|website=lstscorereports.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nDedman School of Law in  2014 ranked #1  among Texas law schools\u2019 placement for permanent, full-time jobs requiring bar passage and professional jobs where a JD is an advantage, that were not funded by the law school.\n\n==Costs==\nThe total cost of attendance (indicating the cost of tuition, fees, and living expenses) at SMU for the 2020-2021 academic year is $83,464.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu/Law/Admissions/Costs-and-Financial-Aid/Estimated-Cost-of-Attendance|title=Archived copy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714195733/http://www.law.smu.edu/Prospective-Students/Fast-Facts.aspx#2014-2015|archive-date=2014-07-14|access-date=2014-07-10}}</ref> The average amount borrowed for law school by members of the 2014 graduating class was $124,617.38.\n\n==Notable faculty==\n* [[Bryan Garner]]\n*[[Paul Hardin III]]\n*[[A. Kenneth Pye]]\n*[[Dale Carpenter]]\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Main|List of Southern Methodist University people}}\n\n<!--\n\nPLEASE: maintain this list in alphabetical order.\nPLEASE: Only include people who already have Wikipedia articles.\n\nThe Law School has numerous alumni that are Fortune 500 CEOs, general counsel to Fortune 500 companies, Chief Justices on the Supreme Courts of foreign sovereigns, federal circuit court judges, and governmental representatives, senators, and officers.\n-->\n* [[Keith Bergelt]], former U.S. Diplomat and CEO of [[Open Invention Network]]\n* Michael Boone, founder of [[Haynes and Boone, LLP]]\n* [[Jane J. Boyle]] is a district judge for the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Texas]]\n* [[Angela Braly]], former President and Chief Executive Officer for WellPoint (now [[Anthem (company)|Anthem]])\n*[[Raleigh Brown]] - member of the [[Texas House of Representatives]]; Texas State District Court judge in [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Raleigh Brown|url=https://duckduckgo.com/1/c/Southern_Methodist_University_alumni|publisher=Southern Methodist University}}</ref>\n*[[Jeff Cox (Louisiana judge)|Jeff Cox]] (Legal Law Masters in Taxation) - judge since 2005 of the Louisiana 26th Judicial District Court of Bossier and Webster parishes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.26jdc.com/# |title=Judge Jeff Cox |publisher=26jdc.com |accessdate=April 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517001256/http://26jdc.com/ |archivedate=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n*[[Robert H. Dedman Jr.]] former CEO of [[ClubCorp]]\n* [[Robert H. Dedman Sr.]] founder of private club network [[ClubCorp]], Inc.  and the law school\u2019s co-benefactor\n* [[Craig T. Enoch]] is a former associate justice of the [[Texas Supreme Court]]\n* [[Gerald J. Ford]] noted Texas banker and businessman\n* [[David C. Godbey]] - federal judge\n* [[Rusty Hardin]] is an American attorney and head of the Houston law firm Rusty Hardin & Associates, P.C\n* [[O.H. \"Ike\" Harris]], [[Texas State Senate|Texas State Senator]]\n* [[Nathan Hecht]] is the Chief Justice of the [[Texas Supreme Court]]\n* [[Todd Ames Hunter]], [[Texas House of Representatives|Texas State Representative]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/5532/todd-hunter#.UyRv7ctOUfg|title=Todd Hunter's Biography|publisher=votesmart.com|accessdate=March 15, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Ray Hutchison]] (B.A. '57, J.D. '59) - former Texas state representative  {{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n*[[Jerry Jones, Jr.]], Chief Sales and Marketing Officer and Executive Vice President of the [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n* [[S. M. Krishna]], Minister of External Affairs of India\n* [[Stephen N. Limbaugh, Jr.]] - Justice, [[Supreme Court of Missouri]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Stephen N. Limbaugh, Jr.|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=3177&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|accessdate=16 May 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Barbara M.G. Lynn]] - Judge, [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Texas]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Barbara M.G. Lynn|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=2849&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|accessdate=16 May 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Robert B. Maloney]] - federal judge\n* [[Bagir Manan]] - [[Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of Indonesia]]{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n* [[Robert Mosbacher, Jr.]] is an American businessman, founder of BizCorps\n* [[Harriet Miers]] White House Deputy Chief of Staff, White House Counsel for [[George W. Bush]]\n* [[John Ratcliffe (American politician)|John Ratcliffe]] is an American politician who serves as the Congressman for [[Texas's 4th congressional district]]\n* [[Trevor Rees-Jones (businessman)|Trevor Rees-Jones]] founder and chairman of [[Chief Oil & Gas]]\n* [[Joe Rollins|Joseph Guy Rollins, Jr.]] ('41) -  [[Houston, Texas|Houston]] lawyer{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n* [[Robert Rowling]] founder of TRT Holdings, the holding company of [[Omni Hotels & Resorts]] and [[Gold's Gym]]\n* [[Edward B. Rust, Jr.]] chairman and chief executive officer of [[State Farm]] Mutual Automobile Insurance Company\n* [[Rick Scott]] American businessman, politician and 45th [[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]\n* [[Kenneth Sheets]] (J.D. 2004) - Dallas attorney and Republican member of the Texas House of Representatives from District 107 in Dallas County since 2011<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.texastribune.org/directory/kenneth-sheets/#ui-tabs-1|title=State Rep. Kenneth Sheets District 107 (R-Dallas)|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=March 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323055237/http://www.texastribune.org/directory/kenneth-sheets/#ui-tabs-1|archive-date=March 23, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Lamar S. Smith]] is the [[U.S. Representative]] for [[Texas's 21st congressional district]]\n* [[Helmut Sohmen]] chairman of [[BW Group]] and a former Hong Kong legislator\n* [[William Steger]] - Judge, [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Texas]]<ref>{{cite web|title=William Steger|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=2281&cid=999|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|accessdate=16 May 2013}}</ref>\n<!-- Tsai Hong-tu alphabetized according to his surname, which in Chinese names occurs first. -->\n* [[Tsai Hong-tu]] is a Taiwanese businessman and banker\n* [[Lamar White]] investigative journalist known for his work on racism and political corruption in the Deep South\n* [[James Baker]] Justice of the Texas Supreme Court\n*[[Haechang Chung]] former Minister of Justice and Chief of Staff to the President of Korea\n*[[David Godbey]] federal judge\n*[[Nathan Hecht]] Texas Supreme Court Chief Justice\n*[[Yukio Horigome]] Justice, Supreme Court of Japan\n*[[James Latane Noel, Jr.]] Attorney General of Texas\n*[[Gillian Triggs]] President of the Australian Human Rights Commission\n*[[Bagir Manan]] Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of Indonesia\n*[[Paul Hart]] General Counsel for Mark Cuban\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.law.smu.edu}}\n\n{{Southern Methodist University}}\n{{Law Schools of the Southwest}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dedman School Of Law}}\n[[Category:Southern Methodist University colleges and schools|Law, Dedman School of]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Texas]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1925]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{peacock|date=November 2017}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox law school\n|name            = Dedman School of Law\n|native_name     =\n|latin_name      =\n|motto           = ''Veritas Liberabit Vos''\n|mottoeng        = ''The Truth Shall Set You Free''\n|image           = SMU Dedman Law.png\n|image_size      = 300px\n|established     = 1925\n|type            = [[Private university|Private]]\n|endowment       = $1.633 billion (parent institution for FY 2019)\n|faculty         = 50 full-time; 10 emeritus; 94 adjunct\n|dean            = Jennifer M. Collins\n|coordinates     = {{coord|32.8464|-96.7861|type:edu_region:US-TX|display=it}}\n|students        = 900\n|ranking         = 56nd (2021)<ref>{{cite web |title=Southern Methodist University (Dedman) |url=https://premium.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/southern-methodist-university-03150}}</ref>\n|city            = [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]\n|state           = [[Texas]]\n|country         = U.S.\n|campus          = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|affiliations    =\n|parent          = [[Southern Methodist University]]\n|website         = {{url|www.law.smu.edu}}\n}}\n\n'''SMU Dedman School of Law''', commonly referred to as '''SMU Law School''' or '''Dedman School of Law'''  is a prominent professional [[graduate school|graduate]] [[law school]] located in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]]. It was founded in February 1925. SMU Law School is located on the  campus of its parent institution, [[Southern Methodist University]]\n\nSMU\u2019s Law School was renamed SMU Dedman School of Law in February 2001 in honor of its late benefactors, [[Robert H. Dedman Sr.]] and his wife, Nancy Dedman. SMU Law School was the only law school in Dallas until UNT opened its law school four years ago. The current dean of the law school is Jennifer Collins.\n\nSome of the Law School\u2019s alumni include White House Counsel, Chairs of the House Judiciary Committee, Foreign Minister of India, Chief Justices of Indonesia and Thailand, and the Chief Legal Counsel of AT&T and Mark Cuban Companies.\n\nSMU Dedman School of Law is one of ten law schools in Texas. The school has graduated five Fortune 500 Chief Executives (the most of any school according to Business Insider), justices of the Texas Supreme Court, federal and state judges, and several U.S. and state government officials, senators, and representatives.<br />\n\n<br />\n\n==Academic Profile==\nSMU Dedman School of Law offers [[Juris Doctor]], [[Master of Laws]], and [[Doctor of Juridical Science]] degrees.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.law.smu.edu/Default.aspx?DN=724ecf69-7fc0-4f58-956f-4640dd453d70 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-07-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815075056/http://www.law.smu.edu/Default.aspx?DN=724ecf69-7fc0-4f58-956f-4640dd453d70 |archive-date=2009-08-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The school offers two joint degree programs, a J.D./M.A. in Economics and a J.D./M.B.A. The J.D./M.A. in Economics is offered in connection with the SMU Department of Economics in [[Dedman College]] and the J.D./M.B.A. is offered in connection with the [[Cox School of Business]].[[File:SMU Dallas.jpg|thumb|266x266px|Aerial view of the SMU Campus with downtown Dallas]]The class that enrolled in the fall of 2019 has a median LSAT score of 161 and a median undergraduate GPA of 3.7. LSAT/UGPA medians were calculated by the Law School Admission Council based on matriculant lists provided by the law school to the American Bar Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu/Law/Admissions/FAQs|title=FAQs {{!}} SMU Dedman School of Law {{!}} Dallas Texas|website=www.smu.edu|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\nEach JD student must complete 87 credit hours. Thirty-one of these hours comprise the mandatory first-year curriculum. After the first year, students must complete a course in professional responsibility, two upper-level writing courses (including an edited writing seminar in which an extensive scholarly, expository writing project is reviewed and critiqued by the professor), Constitutional Law II, and a practical skills course.  All students are required to perform 30 hours of public service before graduating. <br />\n\n==Programs and Resources==\nDedman Law is home to five independent [[law journals]]: ''The SMU Law Review'', ''[[The International Lawyer]]'', ''Journal of Air Law and Commerce'', ''[[Law and Business Review of the Americas]]'', and the ''SMU Science & Technology Law Review''.\n\nServing the community since 1947, Dedman Law offers several [[law clinic]]s for upper-division students where, under the supervision of clinic directors, our students serve as advocates on behalf of the community in many areas of the law.  The law clinics include: the W.W. Caruth, Jr. Child Advocacy Clinic, Civil Clinic, Criminal Justice Clinic, Family Immigration Detention Clinic, Federal Taxpayers Clinic, First Amendment Clinic, Consumer Advocacy Project, Small Business Clinic & Trademark Clinic, Judge Elmo B. Hunter Legal Center for Victims of Crimes Against Women, Innocence Clinic, Patent Law Clinic, and Vansickle Family Law Clinic.\n\nDedman Law offers a summer program at the [[University of Oxford]] in [[Oxford, England]], numerous international programs, and Underwood Law Library.\n[[File:Underwood Library.jpg|thumb|SMU Underwood Library|291x291px]]\n\n==Underwood Law Library==\nSMU\u2019s Underwood Law Library is the largest private academic law library west of the Mississippi River .<ref name=\"smu.edu\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu/Law/Library/About|title=Archived copy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814095627/http://library.law.smu.edu/About-Us/Library-Facts|archive-date=2016-08-14|access-date=2016-07-13}}</ref> Its collections include approximately 662,465 law-related volumes and equivalents, ranking the library among the top 20% of all law libraries in the United States.<ref name=\"smu.edu\"/>\n\n==Rankings==\nIn 2019, SMU Dedman School of Law was ranked No. 52 in the nation by [[U.S. News & World Report]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/southern-methodist-university-03150|title=Archived copy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Wv34IyBQ?url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-rankings/page+2|archive-date=2015-03-10|access-date=2014-03-11}}</ref>\n\nThe ''National Law Journal'' has ranked SMU Dedman School of Law 28th in \u201cgo-to\u201d law schools.\n\n''Business Insider'' ranked SMU Dedman School of Law 21st in Law schools that have the best alumni for networking and finding legal jobs and 32nd overall. SmartClass ranked Dedman between 24th and 37th in the nation from 2008 until today rising every year since the ranking's inception.\n\nThe school was ranked 8th in the nation for Tax Law and 3rd in the nation for real estate law by [[Law Street Media]].\n\nSSRN ranked Dedman in the top 30 law schools utilizing a new methodology that assimilates bar passage rates, employment statistics, Professor access, and other actual performance metrics that accentuate output as opposed to input, such as LSAT scores or undergraduate GPA.\n\nAmong all publications, SMU Law places between 19th and 46th. Excluding their highest and lowest ranking they consistently rank within the top 20\u201330 institutions in America. The school boasts a strong alumni class, top regional placement, and consistently robust employment outcomes (employed 92% of 2018 class within 9 months of graduation and 24% in the NLJ 250).\n\n==Employment==\n[[File:SMU Graduation.jpg|thumb|244x244px|Dedman School of Law Graduates]]\nAccording to SMU's official 2018 ABA-required disclosures, 80% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time, long-term, JD-required employment nine months after graduation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu/Law/Career-Services/Employment-Statistics/ABA-Employment-Summary-for-Class-of-2018|title=Archived copy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704072339/http://www.law.smu.edu/Career-Services/Employment-Statistics.aspx|archive-date=2014-07-04|access-date=2014-07-10}}</ref> SMU's [[Law School Transparency]] under-employment score is 10.8%, indicating the percentage of the Class of 2018 unemployed, pursuing an additional degree, or working in a non-professional, short-term, or part-time job nine months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lstreports.com/schools/smu/|title=Southern Methodist University|last=|first=|date=|website=lstscorereports.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nDedman School of Law in  2014 ranked #1  among Texas law schools\u2019 placement for permanent, full-time jobs requiring bar passage and professional jobs where a JD is an advantage, that were not funded by the law school.\n\n==Costs==\nThe total cost of attendance (indicating the cost of tuition, fees, and living expenses) at SMU for the 2020-2021 academic year is $83,464.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu/Law/Admissions/Costs-and-Financial-Aid/Estimated-Cost-of-Attendance|title=Archived copy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714195733/http://www.law.smu.edu/Prospective-Students/Fast-Facts.aspx#2014-2015|archive-date=2014-07-14|access-date=2014-07-10}}</ref> The average amount borrowed for law school by members of the 2014 graduating class was $124,617.38.\n\n==Notable faculty==\n* [[Bryan Garner]]\n*[[Paul Hardin III]]\n*[[A. Kenneth Pye]]\n*[[Dale Carpenter]]\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Main|List of Southern Methodist University people}}\n\n<!--\n\nPLEASE: maintain this list in alphabetical order.\nPLEASE: Only include people who already have Wikipedia articles.\n\nThe Law School has numerous alumni that are Fortune 500 CEOs, general counsel to Fortune 500 companies, Chief Justices on the Supreme Courts of foreign sovereigns, federal circuit court judges, and governmental representatives, senators, and officers.\n-->\n* [[Keith Bergelt]], former U.S. Diplomat and CEO of [[Open Invention Network]]\n* Michael Boone, founder of [[Haynes and Boone, LLP]]\n* [[Jane J. Boyle]] is a district judge for the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Texas]]\n* [[Angela Braly]], former President and Chief Executive Officer for WellPoint (now [[Anthem (company)|Anthem]])\n*[[Raleigh Brown]] - member of the [[Texas House of Representatives]]; Texas State District Court judge in [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Raleigh Brown|url=https://duckduckgo.com/1/c/Southern_Methodist_University_alumni|publisher=Southern Methodist University}}</ref>\n*[[Jeff Cox (Louisiana judge)|Jeff Cox]] (Legal Law Masters in Taxation) - judge since 2005 of the Louisiana 26th Judicial District Court of Bossier and Webster parishes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.26jdc.com/# |title=Judge Jeff Cox |publisher=26jdc.com |accessdate=April 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517001256/http://26jdc.com/ |archivedate=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n*[[Robert H. Dedman Jr.]] former CEO of [[ClubCorp]]\n* [[Robert H. Dedman Sr.]] founder of private club network [[ClubCorp]], Inc.  and the law school\u2019s co-benefactor\n* [[Craig T. Enoch]] is a former associate justice of the [[Texas Supreme Court]]\n* [[Gerald J. Ford]] noted Texas banker and businessman\n* [[David C. Godbey]] - federal judge\n* [[Rusty Hardin]] is an American attorney and head of the Houston law firm Rusty Hardin & Associates, P.C\n* [[O.H. \"Ike\" Harris]], [[Texas State Senate|Texas State Senator]]\n* [[Nathan Hecht]] is the Chief Justice of the [[Texas Supreme Court]]\n* [[Todd Ames Hunter]], [[Texas House of Representatives|Texas State Representative]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/5532/todd-hunter#.UyRv7ctOUfg|title=Todd Hunter's Biography|publisher=votesmart.com|accessdate=March 15, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Ray Hutchison]] (B.A. '57, J.D. '59) - former Texas state representative  {{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n*[[Jerry Jones, Jr.]], Chief Sales and Marketing Officer and Executive Vice President of the [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n* [[S. M. Krishna]], Minister of External Affairs of India\n* [[Stephen N. Limbaugh, Jr.]] - Justice, [[Supreme Court of Missouri]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Stephen N. Limbaugh, Jr.|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=3177&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|accessdate=16 May 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Barbara M.G. Lynn]] - Judge, [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Texas]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Barbara M.G. Lynn|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=2849&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|accessdate=16 May 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Robert B. Maloney]] - federal judge\n* [[Bagir Manan]] - [[Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of Indonesia]]{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n* [[Robert Mosbacher, Jr.]] is an American businessman, founder of BizCorps\n* [[Harriet Miers]] White House Deputy Chief of Staff, White House Counsel for [[George W. Bush]]\n* [[John Ratcliffe (American politician)|John Ratcliffe]] is an American politician who serves as the Congressman for [[Texas's 4th congressional district]]\n* [[Trevor Rees-Jones (businessman)|Trevor Rees-Jones]] founder and chairman of [[Chief Oil & Gas]]\n* [[Joe Rollins|Joseph Guy Rollins, Jr.]] ('41) -  [[Houston, Texas|Houston]] lawyer{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}\n* [[Robert Rowling]] founder of TRT Holdings, the holding company of [[Omni Hotels & Resorts]] and [[Gold's Gym]]\n* [[Edward B. Rust, Jr.]] chairman and chief executive officer of [[State Farm]] Mutual Automobile Insurance Company\n* [[Rick Scott]] American businessman, politician and 45th [[List of Governors of Florida|Governor of Florida]]\n* [[Kenneth Sheets]] (J.D. 2004) - Dallas attorney and Republican member of the Texas House of Representatives from District 107 in Dallas County since 2011<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.texastribune.org/directory/kenneth-sheets/#ui-tabs-1|title=State Rep. Kenneth Sheets District 107 (R-Dallas)|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=March 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323055237/http://www.texastribune.org/directory/kenneth-sheets/#ui-tabs-1|archive-date=March 23, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Lamar S. Smith]] is the [[U.S. Representative]] for [[Texas's 21st congressional district]]\n* [[Helmut Sohmen]] chairman of [[BW Group]] and a former Hong Kong legislator\n* [[William Steger]] - Judge, [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Texas]]<ref>{{cite web|title=William Steger|url=http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=2281&cid=999|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|accessdate=16 May 2013}}</ref>\n<!-- Tsai Hong-tu alphabetized according to his surname, which in Chinese names occurs first. -->\n* [[Tsai Hong-tu]] is a Taiwanese businessman and banker\n* [[Lamar White]] investigative journalist known for his work on racism and political corruption in the Deep South\n* [[James Baker]] Justice of the Texas Supreme Court\n*[[Haechang Chung]] former Minister of Justice and Chief of Staff to the President of Korea\n*[[David Godbey]] federal judge\n*[[Nathan Hecht]] Texas Supreme Court Chief Justice\n*[[Yukio Horigome]] Justice, Supreme Court of Japan\n*[[James Latane Noel, Jr.]] Attorney General of Texas\n*[[Gillian Triggs]] President of the Australian Human Rights Commission\n*[[Bagir Manan]] Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of Indonesia\n*[[Paul Hart]] General Counsel for Mark Cuban\n\n==References==\n{{Ref